T_ID['flashbulbmemory']='<b>flashbulb memory:</b> a clear memory of an emotionally significant moment or event. (p. 311)</p>';
T_ID['flow']='<b>flow:</b> a completely involved, focused state of consciousness, with diminished awareness of self and time, resulting from optimal engagement of one&#8217;s skills. (p. 441)</p>';
T_ID['fluidintelligence']='<b>fluid intelligence:</b> our ability to reason speedily and abstractly; tends to decrease during late adulthood. (p. 384)</p>';
T_ID['fmrifunctionalmri']='<b>fMRI (functional MRI):</b> a technique for revealing bloodflow and, therefore, brain activity by comparing successive MRI scans. fMRI scans show brain function. (p. 62)</p>';
T_ID['footinthedoorphenomenon']='<b>foot-in-the-door phenomenon:</b> the tendency for people who have first agreed to a small request to comply later with a larger request. (p. 557)</p>';
T_ID['formaloperationalstage']='<b>formal operational stage:</b> in Piaget&#8217;s theory, the stage of cognitive development (normally beginning about age 12) during which people begin to think logically about abstract concepts. (p. 179)</p>';
T_ID['fovea']='<b>fovea:</b> the central focal point in the retina, around which the eye&#8217;s cones cluster. (p. 229)</p>';
T_ID['framing']='<b>framing:</b> the way an issue is posed; how an issue is framed can significantly affect decisions and judgments. (p. 344)</p>';
T_ID['fraternaltwins']='<b>fraternal twins:</b> twins who develop from separate (dizygotic) fertilized eggs. They are genetically no closer than brothers and sisters, but they share a fetal environment. (p. 132)</p>';
T_ID['freeassociation']='<b>free association:</b> in psychoanalysis, a method of exploring the unconscious in which the person relaxes and says whatever comes to mind, no matter how trivial or embarrassing. (p. 514)</p>';
T_ID['frequency']='<b>frequency:</b> the number of complete wavelengths that pass a point in a given time (for example, per second). (p. 244)</p>';
T_ID['frequencytheory']='<b>frequency theory:</b> in hearing, the theory that the rate of nerve impulses traveling up the auditory nerve matches the frequency of a tone, thus enabling us to sense its pitch. (p. 247)</p>';
T_ID['frontallobes']='<b>frontal lobes:</b> portion of the cerebral cortex lying just behind the forehead; involved in speaking and muscle movements and in making plans and judgments. (p. 69)</p>';
